Results

Hypothesis 1

Figure 1. Estimates of how the proportion that holds the opinion with universal argument advantage (in essence, the liberal opinion) has trended over time, averaged over 54 moral issues covered by the General Social Survey.

Hypothesis 2

Correlation between the verbal ability effect and UAA.

## [1] "*r* (95) = 0.69, 95% CI [0.57, 0.78], p < 0.001. R squared = 0.48"

A linear regression effect after recoding.

## [1] "$\\beta$ = 0.48, 95% CI [0.28, 0.68], t(95) = 4.8, p < 0.001. R squared 0.19"

Figure 2. The effect of verbal ability upon 97 moral opinions plotted against the UAA of the same opinion. Regression line with 95% confidence interval.

Hypothesis 3

Figure 3. The same scatter plot as in Figure 1 for verbal ability effects calculated within each of seven ideology-based segments of the population.
